//
// Further Up the River, Matthew Arcus, mla, 2020.
// Derived from https://www.shadertoy.com/view/Wd2yzd by sl2c
//
// Shows the (2,3,infinity) hyperbolic tiling, with a hyperbolic
// translation preserving the fixed points of a Mobius transform
// (+-1/sqrt(2) in fact). Apeirogon borders are shown forming a
// "river" with tributaries (as described below).
//
// Controls:
// b: unshifted map as background
// f: highlight fixed points
// h: halfplane
// r: highlight river
// t: tiling
// 
// Shader shows the (2,3,infinity) tiling of the hyperbolic plane, either
// the disc or halfplane model. This tiling divides the plane up into
// an infinite number of apeirogons - infinite sided polyhedra - which
// touch the real line at rational points, in the halfplane
// model. Define an integral (real) Mobius transformation, T(x) =
// (ax+b)/(cx+d), lift this to work on the whole complex plane,
// preserving the real axis (or unit circle). Generally T 
// has two fixed points (solve the quadratic) which divide the real
// line in two parts, with T(x)-x < 0 in one part, T(x)-x > 0 in the
// other part. If x is rational, we can expand T(x)-x = T(p/q)-p/q to
// get a binary quadratic form (substitute p/q for x and expand): Ap^2
// + Bpq + Cq^2, which takes values < 0 in one of those parts, and > 0
// in the other part, so we can divide the apeirogons of the tiling
// into two sets, depending on the quadratic form's value at the point
// the apeirogon touches the real line, so the River of the title is
// the line that divides these sets, and in fact has a periodic
// structure.
//
