// The CubeA is a great texture which can hold a lot of data. Being fixed sized, 
// it is ideal to store all kinds of large structures.
// It contains 6 planes of 1024x1024 pixels. A CubeA pixel consist of 4 low-precision
// components (4x16 bits), so in theory we could store 384 Mbit = 48 MByte there!
// There is one important limitation: we cannot use all 16 bits of a component.
// By using unpackHalf2x16 and packHalf2x16 we can pack 2x 16-bit uints into 2x low precision
// floats and vice-versa. However we seem to loose some precision, maybe because converting low
// precision float to high precision floats (the native type in GLSL) and back.
// Not every bit combination seems to lead to a valid float (think of NaN).
//
// At my system (Windows 10, both Firefox and Chrome, ANGLE) this has the effect that in a range
// of 0..FFFF there are two ranges that will not be correctly converted: 7C00..7FFF and FC00..FFFF
// (indicated by the two red bars in the graph).
// So effectively we can only use 15 of the 16 bits (not using bit 14).
//
// I'm curious if this is videocard/GLSL version dependent and if everybody experiences the same
// effect. If that's the case, we can still store 360 MBit = 45 MByte, which is still a huge amount!

// Doesn't seem to have effect:
precision lowp float;

// - Zoom in on first range 7C00..7FFF
